defaultIntegrated servicesdefault7.1.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThere are many reasons why local agencies have difficulties with integrated working. For instance, d
defaultifferent agencies often use different terminology and this can hinder integrated working. There needs to be a shared understanding of mental health and wellbeing, and of the range of services that are required, and what the responsibilities are for each agency. 
default7.2.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultRelevant services in a given area need to work in genuine partnership to plan, commission and deliver the full range of mental health services including those for long-term conditions. The different agencies need to have a mandate and incentives to encourage them to work in partnership. There also needs to be good leadership within these agencies to drive forward partnership working. Partnership working relies on trust, and this needs to be nurtured and developed through good working relationships between staff in different agencies. 
default7.3.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultHealth and Wellbeing Boards are in a good position to improve integrated working. In order for these new bodies to achieve this, they must have representation from voluntary sector organisations, the justice system, and education, as well as the members stipulated in the Health and Social Care Act 2012. This will enable 
defaulta 
defaultwide range of agencies to come together and feed in to the
defaultir 
defaultlocal 
defaultjoint strategic n
defaulteeds 
defaultassessment (JSNA) and their joint health and wellbeing strategy.
default7.4.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultHea
defaultlth and Wellbeing Boards must 
defaultensure that their JSNAs 
defaulttake account of the 
defaultmental health 
defaultneeds of children and young people
default. This needs analysis data must be 
defaultreflected in their joint health and wellbeing strategies and ultimately in the local commissioning plans
default of the clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) and the local authority.
